19 hostages released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts kidnapped ten days ago.
I'm in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts held captive in the desert for ten days were brought back to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon, safe and sound.
In the morning, they were freed in Chad by an Egyptian commando.
Apparently in good shape, the hostages arrived at the Almaza military base near Cairo International Airport at around 3:30 p.m. on board a special plane.
On board a helicopter, they were immediately transferred, without being able to give any interviews to the press, to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for analysis.
They enjoy “good health” and no ransom was paid “to the kidnappers,” Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said on the airstrip.
Kidnapped on September 19 during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, bordering Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been swept from hideout to hideout by 35 unknown kidnappers.
The group consisted of 11 tourists – five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian – and 8 Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of Aegyptus, the agency that organized the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, aboard two helicopters, had launched the assault overnight, just before dawn.
“There were gunshots, half of the kidnappers were killed, while the others fled,” said the official who requested anonymity.
He explained that 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "flash" unit were sent to Sudan, where German and Italian commandos would support them.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini stressed the importance of the role of Italian secret agents and special forces from Belgrade.
We must admit that if we achieved this result it was thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of the men of our secret services, of the special forces,” he said, without adding further details.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese patrol army had claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle in which the kidnappers were, killed six of them, including the Chadian leader of the kidnappers, and captured two of them.
According to the army, the kidnappers were linked to a rebel organization in Darfur, the Sudan Liberation Movement (SLA_U), an assertion immediately denied by the latter.
