Benelux governments nationalise part of Fortis Bank
The Benelux states are helping through partial nationalisation the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which ended up in difficulty first in Europe because of the crisis of the American credit market: the three nations will provide 11.2 billion euros to the financial institution - insurance with interests also in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands agreed at the highest level over the weekend, including the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the difficulties the international financial market has been facing for more than a year is that of Fortis Bank, and from a certain point of view the decisions taken in this regard can set a precedent.
Under the decision taken on Sunday night, all three states will hold nearly half (49%) of the bank’s share in the country.
The bank will almost certainly sell part of its interests, including first of all the assets, especially insurance, of the Dutch ABN Amro acquired a year ago.
Last week, Fortis’ actions began with a vertical collapse, with serious signs of crisis emerging in the second half of the week.
Analysts, however, agree that the bank, with 85,000 employees, is too large to allow it to go bankrupt.
The bank's shares fell nearly 12% on Friday, the lowest point in 14 years.
Since January, the value of the shares has decreased by more than two-thirds.
Considering the current stock prices the entire capital value of the group is around 14 billion euros, but according to the bank's executives this value is not real.
The company blames the collapse of Fortis shares on the uncertainties of the non-European market due to the acceptance of the US $700 billion plan.
On Monday, the title slowly rebounded.
On Friday Filip Dierckx was appointed the new CEO of the bank.
The financial institution has also been looking for private buyers but so far no one has come up with a deserving offer.
The Belgian government had previously assured investors that they should not be afraid of losing money.
Among the bank’s customers there was no panic, the branches were not assaulted.
In Hungary Fortis owns autonomous subsidiaries and has also acquired leasing companies.
The fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurers, based on people’s medical purchase data, often refuse to enter into an insurance contract.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
“There is a privacy program according to which the use of prescription drug data depends in any case on the approval of the person concerned.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it’s like entrusting the chicken coop to the fox,” the Washington Post quoted Richard Dick as citing the program’s author to follow prescriptions for drugs.
Insurance companies subordinate the insurance rate and the amount due in case of claims to the state of health of the possible customer and if they consider the risk too high they do not take out the insurance.
A long time ago the client had to undergo a medical examination and the contract was concluded only after the result of the examination.
Dick 10 years ago invented a much cheaper procedure: based on the customer's identification code you can easily get information from pharmacies about what medicines he has purchased in the last year and a half and from this the program shows which diseases he suffers and in what health condition he is in.
For example, if you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol reducers, this means that the level of fat in your blood is practically incurably high and is classified in the highest risk category.
There are various versions of the program on the market, some also determine the risk multiplier, so in addition to paper work there is not much left to the insurer, even if there are small difficulties.
Among the cons is that some medicines are usable for several purposes, e.g. some compounds are usable against migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter, from an insurance-commercial point of view, applies as a risk-increasing factor, the first two do not.
For the request and processing of data, separate companies have been formed and, before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, they request the approval of the patient.
Now the authorities are forcing them to do so even though they have so far not imposed fines for negligence.
Some companies have also recently been processing the results of laboratory tests and linking them to drug consumption data in order to provide a more accurate picture of patients' health status.
More and more companies have access to the data and at the same time the control of the use will be increasingly difficult.
There is a separate privacy law, but its validity extends only to health services and insurance.
In front of Congress there is a bill that gives the authorities supervisory competence to companies specializing in data service.
Richard Dick admits that it is not enough: for this reason he has developed a program that connects the forwarding of data with the express approval of the person concerned.
Another issue is that the person concerned cannot so much deny approval because otherwise the insurers do not enter into the contract.
So then in the end the hens are entrusted to the fox's clemency.
