EU and India double trade
Given that the European Union and India are partners who trade mainly with each other, the agenda of the ninth summit meeting has also been dominated by this theme, in addition to all other global problems.
Today there will be a Franco-Indian summit which will deal primarily with cooperation on atomic energy.
The European Union recognizes that India is becoming a great democratic power that should be given more voice in international affairs, but member countries have not yet been able to decide whether or not to support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
So there was no insistence on this issue at the ninth summit held yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, as President of the Union, José Manuel Barroso, Chairman of the Commission, and Javier Solana, High Representative for Foreign Affairs, received Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed to double trade in five years, that is to say to increase trade to 100 billion euros.
Considering that between 2000 and 2007 trade in goods rose from $25 billion to $55 billion, this is not an overly ambitious goal.
As a result, they have legally unified the 26 bilateral civil flight agreements, so air traffic can also take off in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy has promised to speed up the deal.
The goal is to balance because while the EU is India's top trading partner, New Delhi is only ninth among the EU's partners.
